Good question. Three things that complete the picture:

### 1. Shared `createErrorFormatter` factory in `@vendor/observability/trpc`

The `errorFormatter` is **still duplicated** character-for-character between `api/app/src/trpc.ts` and `api/platform/src/trpc.ts` — same pattern we just fixed with `createObservabilityMiddleware`. Co-locate it:

```typescript
// vendor/observability/src/trpc.ts (add to existing file)
export function createErrorFormatter() {
  const isProduction = process.env.NODE_ENV === "production";
  return ({ shape, error }: { shape: DefaultErrorShape; error: TRPCError }) => {
    const httpStatus = getHTTPStatusCodeFromError(error);
    return {
      ...shape,
      message: isProduction && error.code === "INTERNAL_SERVER_ERROR"
        ? "An unexpected error occurred"
        : shape.message,
      data: {
        ...shape.data,
        isUserFacing: httpStatus < 500,
        zodError: error.cause instanceof ZodError ? error.cause.flatten() : null,
      },
    };
  };
}
```

Both API packages become one-liners:

```typescript
const t = initTRPC.context<typeof createTRPCContext>().create({
  transformer: superjson,
  errorFormatter: createErrorFormatter(),
});
```

This means the classification logic (`httpStatus < 500`), the sanitization logic (`INTERNAL_SERVER_ERROR` → generic message), and the Zod flattening all live in **one file** alongside the middleware. Single place to change, single place to understand.

### 2. Typed mutation `meta` via module augmentation

Without this, `meta.errorTitle` and `meta.suppressErrorToast` are `any`-typed — no autocomplete, no compiler help. One declaration:

```typescript
// packages/app-trpc/src/meta.ts
declare module "@tanstack/react-query" {
  interface MutationMeta {
    /** Custom toast title for mutation errors. Default: "Something went wrong" */
    errorTitle?: string;
    /** Skip the global error toast (for mutations with inline error display). */
    suppressErrorToast?: boolean;
  }
}
```

Now when a developer writes `meta: { error` they get autocomplete. TypeScript catches typos like `meta: { supressErrorToast: true }`.

### 3. Fix `OrgPageErrorBoundary` to use structured data

Replace the string matching (`error.message.includes("not found")`) with the typed field that's already on the wire:

```typescript
// Before: string matching on message content (brittle)
const message = error.message?.toLowerCase() ?? "";
if (message.includes("access denied") || message.includes("forbidden")) ...

// After: read the typed code field
const data = (error as any).data;
if (data?.code === "FORBIDDEN") errorType = "access_denied";
else if (data?.code === "NOT_FOUND") errorType = "not_found";
```

This can't false-positive on messages that happen to contain "not found" in a different context.

---

### The complete picture

After all of this, a developer's experience for the entire error chain is:

| Concern | Code required | Maintained by |
|---------|--------------|---------------|
| Server error classification | 0 lines | `getHTTPStatusCodeFromError` (tRPC) |
| Sentry capture (server errors only) | 0 lines | `createObservabilityMiddleware` |
| Error shape enrichment | 0 lines | `createErrorFormatter` |
| Mutation error toasts | 0 lines | Global `MutationCache.onError` |
| Custom toast title | 1 line (`meta: { errorTitle }`) | Opt-in |
| Inline error display | 1 line (`meta: { suppressErrorToast }`) | Opt-in |
| Error boundary classification | 0 lines | Reads `error.data.code` |

**Zero constants. Zero manual sets. Zero per-mutation boilerplate. Zero string matching.** The only thing a developer writes is the `throw new TRPCError({ code, message })` on the server — everything else is derived and automatic.

